  },
  "feasibility_assessment": {
    "score": 8,
    "justification": "Proposed experiments using in vitro cultures, animal models, and clinical correlation studies are standard in rheumatology research. Measuring MMP activity, ECM breakdown, and RANK/RANKL expression is well within current methodological capabilities. The hypothesis can likewise be probed by existing RA animal models and clinically by measuring biomarkers in patient samples.",
    "confidence": 0.9
  },
  "impact_assessment": {
    "score": 9,
    "justification": "If validated, this mechanistic chain clarifies a central nodal point (IL-23→MMP axis) in RA bone erosion and suggests new avenues for targeted intervention alongside Denosumab. It has the potential to improve RA patient outcomes by averting bone loss, an important clinical concern that can lead to disability and decreased quality of life.",
    "confidence": 0.85
  },
  "falsifiability_assessment": {
    "score": 9,
    "justification": "Clear operational definitions exist for each component (IL-23 concentrations, MMP expression, RANK/RANKL activation) that can be quantified in human samples or animal models. Failure to detect the predicted changes (e.g., no increase in MMPs after IL-23 stimulation) would refute essential links in the proposed cascade.",
